eate of the British Bolshevist Revolution; and the Chicago Record-Herald’s account of some art students’ “trial” of Henri Matisse for “crimes against anatomy.” An introduction and headnotes by Leonard Diepeveen highlight the usefulness of these pieces for comprehending media and public perceptions of a form of art that would later develop an almost unassailable power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aModernism (Art)xPress coverage. 0aModernism (Art)xPublic opinion. 0aModernism (Literature)xPress coverage. 0aModernism (Literature)xPublic opinion. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266179040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442661790423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442661790.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK